about: The percent of individuals in poverty is determined by comparing a family's total income to an income threshold that varies by family size and composition. For example, in 2018, the poverty threshold for a family with two adults and two children was $25,465. If a family's income is less than the family's poverty threshold, then every member of that family is designated as an individual living in poverty. For more, see https://www.census.gov/topics/income-poverty/poverty/guidance/poverty-measures.html.

The Gini index is a summary measure of income inequality comparing the distribution of income across income percentiles. It ranges from 0, perfect equality (where everyone receives an 
equal share of the overall income), to 1, perfect inequality (where recipients in the top percentile receive all the income). For more, see https://www.census.gov/topics/income-poverty/income-inequality/about/metrics/gini-index.html.

The black-white residential dissimilarity index is a measure of how evenly distributed black and white residents are across census tracts within a locality. The measure ranges from 0, complete residential integration, to 1, complete residential segregation. For more, see https://www.census.gov/hhes/www/housing/resseg/pdf/app_b.pdf.

The Hispanic-White residential dissimilarity index is a measure of how evenly distributed Hispanic and white residents are across census tracts within a locality. The measure ranges from 0, complete residential integration, to 1, complete residential segregation. For more, see https://www.census.gov/hhes/www/housing/resseg/pdf/app_b.pdf.

The black-white residential interaction index is a measure of how much exposure black and white residents have to each other; specifically, the probability that a minority person shares a census tract with a majority person. Low values of interaction indicate greater segregation. For more, see https://www.census.gov/hhes/www/housing/resseg/pdf/app_b.pdf.

The Hispanic-white residential interaction index is a measure of how much exposure Hispanic and white residents have to each other; specifically, the probability that a minority person shares a census tract with a majority person. Low values of interaction indicate greater segregation. https://www.census.gov/hhes/www/housing/resseg/pdf/app_b.pdf.

The black residential isolation index is a measure of how much exposure black residents have to oen another, specifically, the probability that a minority person shares a census tract with another minority person. With little segregation, the measure approaches the overall percent of black residents in the locality; with greater segregation, the measure approaches 1. https://www.census.gov/hhes/www/housing/resseg/pdf/app_b.pdf.

The Hispanic residential isolation index is a measure of how much exposure Hispanic residents have to oen another, specifically, the probability that a minority person shares a census tract with another minority person. With little segregation, the measure approaches the overall percent of Hispanic residents in the locality; with greater segregation, the measure approaches 1.  https://www.census.gov/hhes/www/housing/resseg/pdf/app_b.pdf.
